Christ...’ -- tDo everything in the name of the Lord: Ethics and ethos in Colossians -- t‘A Life Worthy of God’ Identity and Ethics in The Thessalonian Correspondence -- tHeroes at Home: Identity, Ethos, and Ethics in 1 Timothy within the context of the Pastoral Epistles -- tHow Christians can survive in a hostile social-economic environment: Paul's mind concerning difficult social conditions in the Letter to Philemon -- tChapter Four: General Epistles, Hebrews and Revelation -- tMoving in and moving out: Ethics and ethos in Hebrews -- tThe letter of James: Its vision, ethics, and ethos -- tA code of conduct for children of God who suffer unjustly. Identity, Ethics and Ethos in 1 Peter -- tFaithful Christian living amidst scoffers of the Judgment Day: Ethics and ethos in Jude and 2 Peter -- t‘A matter of having fellowship’: Ethics in the Johannine epistles -- tThe ethical response of an alternative community in a critical situation: marturia and martyrdom in the Apocalypse of John -- tChapter Five: 2 Clement -- tThe Motivations of Ethos in 2 Clement -- tSummary -- tAgain: Identity, ethics, and ethos in the New Testament. A few tentative remarks -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Modern Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book deals with the relation between identity, ethics, and ethos in the New Testament. The focus falls on the way in which the commandments or guidelines presented in the New Testament writings inform the behaviour of the intended recipients. The habitual behaviour (ethos) of the different Christian communities in the New Testament are plotted and linked to their identity. Apart from analytical categories like ethos, ethics, and identity that are clearly defined in the book, efforts are also made to broaden the specific analytical categories related to ethical material. The way in which, for instance, narratives, proverbial expressions, imagery, etc. inform the reader about the ethical demands or ethos is also explored.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEthics in the BiblevCongresses. 4aEthik (Theol.). 4aEthos. 4aNeues Testament. 4aUrchristentum. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh  aEthics (theology).  aNew Testament.  aearly christianity.1 aBreytenbach, Cilliers, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCombrink, Η J Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGräbe, Petrus J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartin, Patrick J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHays, Richard B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlauck, Hans-Josef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoubser, J. A. (Bobby), econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalan, François S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerwe, Dirk G. van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratscher, Wilhelm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRand, Jan Α du, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRensburg, Fika J. van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScheffler, Eben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteyn, Gert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTolmie, D F, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aViljoen, Francois P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVilliers, Pieter G. R. de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc